e questions, Robert M. Entman develops a powerful new model of how media framing works—a model that allows him to explain why the media cheered American victories over small-time dictators in Grenada and Panama but barely noticed the success of far more difficult missions in Haiti and Kosovo. Discussing the practical implications of his model, Entman also suggests ways to more effectively encourage the exchange of ideas between the government and the media and between the media and the public. His book will be an essential guide for political scientists, students of the media, and anyone interested in the increasingly influential role of the media in foreign policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  amedia, news, journalism, white house, press coverage, cold war, presidency, foreign policy, framing, spin, public opinion, policymaking, dictators, panama, grenada, kosovo, haiti, government, nonfiction, history, politics, political science, power, libya, iran air, korean airline, iraq, voters, invasion, military, regime change, human rights, intervention.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226210735423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226210735/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles